The divisors of 6 are \(\pm 1, \pm 2, \pm 3, \pm 6\). The product of the roots must be \(-6\) because the constant term is 6. We need to find all sets of three distinct integers from the set \(\{\pm 1, \pm 2, \pm 3, \pm 6\}\) whose product is \(-6\). These sets are: 1. \(\{1, -1, 6\}\) 2. \(\{1, -2, 3\}\) 3. \(\{1, -3, 2\}\) 4. \(\{-1, -2, -3\}\) For each set, we calculate the coefficients \(a\) and \(b\) using the sums and products of the roots: 1. For the set \(\{1, -2, 3\}\): - Sum: \(1 + (-2) + 3 = 2\) �� \(a = -2\) - Product of roots taken two at a time: \((1 \cdot -2) + (1 \cdot 3) + (-2 \cdot 3) = -2 + 3 - 6 = -5\) �� \(b = -5\) - Ordered pair: \((-2, -5)\) 3.
